1
00:00:21,444 --> 00:00:23,143
Today, we're all going out to look at the stars.

2
00:00:23,144 --> 00:00:24,643
We go out looking for a comet and discover a skeleton instead.

3
00:00:24,644 --> 00:00:26,343
Solve the mystery of the scattered cigarettes!

4
00:00:26,344 --> 00:00:27,843
He sees through the one and only truth.

5
00:00:27,844 --> 00:00:29,443
A child in appearance with the I.Q. of an adult.

6
00:00:29,444 --> 00:00:31,244
His name is Detective Conan!

7
00:01:55,645 --> 00:01:57,544
Abnormality observation?

8
00:01:57,545 --> 00:01:59,744
No, Genta.

9
00:01:59,745 --> 00:02:03,244
Astronomical observation, astronomical observation.

10
00:02:03,245 --> 00:02:07,144
Dr. Agasa, are we going to go watch stars from now?

11
00:02:07,145 --> 00:02:11,944
Yeah, I found a nice pension in the mountains of Gunma.

12
00:02:11,945 --> 00:02:14,344
But why are you going outside to watch stars

13
00:02:14,345 --> 00:02:16,544
at a cold time like this?

14
00:02:16,545 --> 00:02:18,844
It's good because it's cold.

15
00:02:18,845 --> 00:02:20,644
The colder it is, the cleaner the air,

16
00:02:20,645 --> 00:02:22,444
and the better it is to watch the stars.

17
00:02:22,445 --> 00:02:24,544
Beside, tonight is the new moon.

18
00:02:24,545 --> 00:02:25,744
In other words,

19
00:02:25,745 --> 00:02:27,944
it's just the night to carry out an astronomical observation.

20
00:02:27,945 --> 00:02:33,244
But, isn't it going to be boring just looking at the stars?

21
00:02:33,245 --> 00:02:35,244
Come on, don't say that.

22
00:02:35,245 --> 00:02:37,244
You can study the stars,

23
00:02:37,245 --> 00:02:40,444
and we may by chance discover a new stars.

24
00:02:40,445 --> 00:02:43,044
If we do, it may be named after us.

25
00:02:43,045 --> 00:02:46,144
-What? Our names! -What? Our names!

26
00:02:46,145 --> 00:02:47,444
A star...

27
00:02:47,445 --> 00:02:49,644
We can name it after ourselves?

28
00:02:49,645 --> 00:02:50,845
Yes, right.

29
00:02:51,845 --> 00:02:54,144
Of course that's impossible

30
00:02:54,145 --> 00:02:55,444
when it comes to asteroids in

31
00:02:55,445 --> 00:02:57,244
which the orbit has to be observed repeatedly

32
00:02:57,245 --> 00:02:59,044
and verified though.

33
00:02:59,045 --> 00:03:00,844
But there is a possibility

34
00:03:00,845 --> 00:03:02,844
if the star is a comet that only requires to be found.

35
00:03:02,845 --> 00:03:06,844
How about calling it Beika Youth Detective Squad Comet?

36
00:03:06,845 --> 00:03:07,944
Sounds nice.

37
00:03:07,945 --> 00:03:10,644
-Nice, isn't it? -Nope.

38
00:03:10,645 --> 00:03:14,544
The only star you can give a name of your choice to is to asteroids.

39
00:03:14,545 --> 00:03:17,144
Comets are named after the surnames of their discoverers,

40
00:03:17,145 --> 00:03:19,144
and moreover, the surnames of only the three people

41
00:03:19,145 --> 00:03:21,244
who submitted their names the earliest can be given to the star.

42
00:03:21,245 --> 00:03:25,244
Right, if a comet is found at the same time all over the world,

43
00:03:25,245 --> 00:03:28,544
it's possible that your name will be mixed with a foreign name.

44
00:03:28,545 --> 00:03:32,544
Three people, me, and...

45
00:03:32,545 --> 00:03:36,544
For example, Kobayashi, Burger, Millon.

46
00:03:36,545 --> 00:03:38,444
So, if we find a comet

47
00:03:38,445 --> 00:03:40,444
and apply for it quickly,

48
00:03:40,445 --> 00:03:45,144
it could be Yoshida Tsuburaya Haibara comet, right?

49
00:03:45,145 --> 00:03:46,544
Yeah, right?

50
00:03:46,545 --> 00:03:48,444
Yes, well...

51
00:03:48,445 --> 00:03:52,544
Yoshida, Tsuburaya, Haibara?

52
00:03:52,545 --> 00:03:55,044
How come my name's not there?

53
00:03:55,045 --> 00:03:57,144
Include Conan's name too.

54
00:03:57,145 --> 00:04:01,144
But it's only up to three names.

55
00:04:01,145 --> 00:04:03,144
Conan, don't you?

56
00:04:03,145 --> 00:04:05,745
Just what are you doing, Conan?

57
00:04:06,845 --> 00:04:08,744
That man. He's the sports reporter, Masaharu Motoyama,

58
00:04:08,745 --> 00:04:11,144
the one that killed the professional baseball player Mr. Nose,

59
00:04:11,145 --> 00:04:14,044
last time in Okinawa, right?

60
00:04:14,045 --> 00:04:17,044
You were there at the time of the incident too, weren't you, Conan?

61
00:04:17,045 --> 00:04:19,944
Yeah. I was bothered about something so...

62
00:04:19,945 --> 00:04:20,945
"Sports reporter, Masaharu Motoyama."

63
00:04:20,946 --> 00:04:22,744
Bothered about what?

64
00:04:22,745 --> 00:04:25,344
Well, it's not such a big deal but...

65
00:04:25,345 --> 00:04:28,344
I was just wondering who he would call on his cell phone

66
00:04:28,345 --> 00:04:31,544
during an interrogation session.

67
00:04:31,545 --> 00:04:33,744
The police already would've contacted

68
00:04:33,745 --> 00:04:38,044
the late Mr. Nose's parents and family so...

69
00:04:38,045 --> 00:04:41,144
I think it's Mr. Motoyama's personal acquaintance.

70
00:04:41,145 --> 00:04:45,844
Darn! I should've directly asked him who he called.

71
00:04:45,845 --> 00:04:47,744
Maybe...

72
00:04:47,745 --> 00:04:49,744
it was baseball player Kobayashi?

73
00:04:49,745 --> 00:04:54,044
The one who entered the team at the same time as Mr. Motoyama.

74
00:04:54,045 --> 00:04:58,044
They were on an off-season travel program together, all three of them,

75
00:04:58,045 --> 00:04:59,944
and seemed to get along well together.

76
00:04:59,945 --> 00:05:03,844
There's a possibility he informed him of the death of his best friend.

77
00:05:03,845 --> 00:05:06,944
He seems to have succeeded his parents' Japanese inn

78
00:05:06,945 --> 00:05:08,544
after he retired four years ago.

79
00:05:08,545 --> 00:05:12,744
If I remember correctly, it was in a place called Kurayoshi in Tottori.

80
00:05:12,745 --> 00:05:15,444
I saw it when it was introduced on TV once,

81
00:05:15,445 --> 00:05:17,844
but it looked to be a nice inn.

82
00:05:17,845 --> 00:05:19,345
I see.

83
00:05:20,645 --> 00:05:24,245
It seems to have nothing to do with the men in black.

84
00:05:27,945 --> 00:05:29,844
Kurayoshi.

85
00:05:29,845 --> 00:05:32,445
Shinichi, don't tell me that you're...

86
00:05:39,645 --> 00:05:44,745
"Stars, a Cigarette and a Code (Part 1)"

87
00:05:45,445 --> 00:05:48,044
Mr. Agasa, right? We've been waiting for you.

88
00:05:48,045 --> 00:05:50,144
Please sign your name on our guest list.

89
00:05:50,145 --> 00:05:51,944
All right.

90
00:05:51,945 --> 00:05:53,844
Hiroshi Agasa.

91
00:05:53,845 --> 00:05:55,544
Where is he?

92
00:05:55,545 --> 00:05:56,644
"Etsuko Nonomiya (28), Guest."

93
00:05:56,645 --> 00:05:59,945
He told you to come here too, didn't he?

94
00:06:00,945 --> 00:06:02,844
Please tell me.

95
00:06:02,845 --> 00:06:04,844
I want to apologize to him.

96
00:06:04,845 --> 00:06:06,944
Where is Asao?

97
00:06:06,945 --> 00:06:08,344
Asao, who is he?

98
00:06:08,345 --> 00:06:09,644
Don't play dumb with me!

99
00:06:09,645 --> 00:06:11,744
A man wearing the same ring that's a pair with this one!

100
00:06:11,745 --> 00:06:13,144
Asao Kono!

101
00:06:13,145 --> 00:06:16,444
You got an invitation card from him to, didn't you?

102
00:06:16,445 --> 00:06:18,444
Ms. Nonomiya.

103
00:06:18,445 --> 00:06:19,944
Invitation card?

104
00:06:19,945 --> 00:06:24,944
Oh, no, you see, this is our first visit here.

105
00:06:24,945 --> 00:06:27,144
Oh, really?

106
00:06:27,145 --> 00:06:28,545
I'm sorry.

107
00:06:30,445 --> 00:06:32,044
Was that a surprise...

108
00:06:32,045 --> 00:06:34,144
I'm so sorry.

109
00:06:34,145 --> 00:06:35,744
Who is she?

110
00:06:35,745 --> 00:06:37,644
"Amatsuchi (34), Pension Owner" -Her name is Etsuko Nonomiya

111
00:06:37,645 --> 00:06:40,844
and she's an under classman of the university that I went to.

112
00:06:40,845 --> 00:06:42,144
The man, Kono that she was referring to

113
00:06:42,145 --> 00:06:44,044
was also an underclassman of my university.

114
00:06:44,045 --> 00:06:46,044
They were engaged.

115
00:06:46,045 --> 00:06:49,844
They used to come and stay over here a lot together in the past,

116
00:06:49,845 --> 00:06:53,044
but after they had a big fight here a year ago,

117
00:06:53,045 --> 00:06:56,044
he stopped coming all together.

118
00:06:56,045 --> 00:06:58,044
Then last week, she seems to have received

119
00:06:58,045 --> 00:07:01,544
an invitation card asking her to come here

120
00:07:01,545 --> 00:07:04,144
and she's been waiting here for the past three days.

121
00:07:04,145 --> 00:07:06,744
Since he hasn't shown up at all,

122
00:07:06,745 --> 00:07:09,044
she's been that way drinking from day time.

123
00:07:09,045 --> 00:07:12,444
But, why would she think that I, who she hasn't even met before

124
00:07:12,445 --> 00:07:15,044
would also get an invitation card?

125
00:07:15,045 --> 00:07:17,144
It's only natural.

126
00:07:17,145 --> 00:07:20,144
"Mikami, Futagawa" -Because we who don't even know him all that well,

127
00:07:20,145 --> 00:07:24,344
got an invitation card from that guy called Kono.

128
00:07:24,345 --> 00:07:29,444
Well, we met him once over here a year ago that day.

129
00:07:29,445 --> 00:07:31,944
Being that the subject in the invitation card was what it is,

130
00:07:31,945 --> 00:07:33,444
we decided to at least come here.

131
00:07:33,445 --> 00:07:36,944
May I see the invitation card?

132
00:07:36,945 --> 00:07:38,944
Yeah, here.

133
00:07:38,945 --> 00:07:40,145
Thank you.

134
00:07:43,345 --> 00:07:45,344
As a result of my one year observation,

135
00:07:45,345 --> 00:07:48,944
I have come up with a discovery that would shake the basis of astronomy.

136
00:07:48,945 --> 00:07:51,144
I would like your opinion on the matter,

137
00:07:51,145 --> 00:07:53,644
so please come to Pension Amatsuchi.

138
00:07:53,645 --> 00:07:56,544
Of course I will foot the room charges.

139
00:07:56,545 --> 00:07:58,144
If you can't come, it can't be helped,

140
00:07:58,145 --> 00:08:02,744
but please make an effort to be there, Asao Kono.

141
00:08:02,745 --> 00:08:05,344
Well, judging from the fact that he's not here,

142
00:08:05,345 --> 00:08:08,844
despite two days already gone by it seems to have been a prank.

143
00:08:08,845 --> 00:08:11,844
Shall we head back then, editor?

144
00:08:11,845 --> 00:08:13,444
Editor?

145
00:08:13,445 --> 00:08:17,844
Yeah, we're writing an astronomical magazine called "Space Sunday".

146
00:08:17,845 --> 00:08:21,245
And, Mr. Mikami here is the editor.

147
00:08:23,045 --> 00:08:25,144
He's no ordinary editor, either.

148
00:08:25,145 --> 00:08:26,344
Oh, come on.

149
00:08:26,345 --> 00:08:27,944
No big deal.

150
00:08:27,945 --> 00:08:32,544
What do you mean by his no ordinary editor?

151
00:08:32,545 --> 00:08:35,644
Well, he discovered a new comet,

152
00:08:35,645 --> 00:08:39,444
and is a great man who a star is named after.

153
00:08:39,445 --> 00:08:40,744
-You... -You discovered one?

154
00:08:40,745 --> 00:08:42,144
Where did you find it?

155
00:08:42,145 --> 00:08:43,844
Tell us where too.

156
00:08:43,845 --> 00:08:46,344
Well, where that's not an easy question.

157
00:08:46,345 --> 00:08:48,545
Over there? Over here?

158
00:08:49,945 --> 00:08:52,544
Then I suggest you climb up the road in back

159
00:08:52,545 --> 00:08:53,845
of the pension to the hill beyond.

160
00:08:55,745 --> 00:08:57,744
It's a scenic viewpoint,

161
00:08:57,745 --> 00:09:00,144
and just great for viewing stars.

162
00:09:00,145 --> 00:09:03,344
If you want, I'll lend you a telescope too.

163
00:09:03,345 --> 00:09:04,845
For 5000 yen.

164
00:09:05,845 --> 00:09:08,244
You're charging us for it.

165
00:09:08,245 --> 00:09:11,344
-Be careful. -Okay!

166
00:09:11,345 --> 00:09:14,744
All right. We'll find our star for sure!

167
00:09:14,745 --> 00:09:16,045
Aye!

168
00:09:17,345 --> 00:09:18,844
Hopeless amateurs.

169
00:09:18,845 --> 00:09:21,844
Don't they know it's not that easy to find.

170
00:09:21,845 --> 00:09:23,145
Right, editor?

171
00:09:24,145 --> 00:09:26,944
No, who knows.

172
00:09:26,945 --> 00:09:28,744
No matter how knowledgeable you are,

173
00:09:28,745 --> 00:09:31,944
whether you can find a star or not depends on luck.

174
00:09:31,945 --> 00:09:35,344
If you're lucky, you can find one.

175
00:09:35,345 --> 00:09:37,644
Right, editor?

176
00:09:37,645 --> 00:09:40,044
Won't you find him for me with your luck

177
00:09:40,045 --> 00:09:42,144
of having found a star?

178
00:09:42,145 --> 00:09:44,144
The guy who was obsessed by stars

179
00:09:44,145 --> 00:09:46,844
and disappeared into the darkness of space.

180
00:09:46,845 --> 00:09:49,745
My precious partner.

181
00:09:54,345 --> 00:09:56,544
It sure is kind of far.

182
00:09:56,545 --> 00:09:58,944
Come on, Dr. Agasa. Hang in there.

183
00:09:58,945 --> 00:10:00,445
Hurry, hurry.

184
00:10:04,945 --> 00:10:07,145
Isn't that the hill?

185
00:10:08,445 --> 00:10:10,744
It's more a cliff than a hill.

186
00:10:10,745 --> 00:10:13,944
You mean we're going to climb way up there?

187
00:10:13,945 --> 00:10:16,044
Let's take a break.

188
00:10:16,045 --> 00:10:18,944
Hey, let's climb up there before sundown.

189
00:10:18,945 --> 00:10:21,344
Treat the aged with kindness.

190
00:10:21,345 --> 00:10:25,544
You're usually telling me not to treat you like the aged.

191
00:10:25,545 --> 00:10:27,744
Shall we rest about ten minutes then?

192
00:10:27,745 --> 00:10:29,244
Agreed!

193
00:10:29,245 --> 00:10:31,645
Darn, come on, man.

194
00:10:38,645 --> 00:10:40,544
A rock, rock...

195
00:10:40,545 --> 00:10:43,745
But, don't you think that invitation was sort of strange?

196
00:10:44,745 --> 00:10:47,544
Would somebody write something like,

197
00:10:47,545 --> 00:10:49,244
"If you can't come, it can't be helped"?

198
00:10:49,245 --> 00:10:50,844
True.

199
00:10:50,845 --> 00:10:52,544
There must've been some urgent reason

200
00:10:52,545 --> 00:10:55,445
he wanted everyone to come here.

201
00:10:57,545 --> 00:10:58,545
I found one!

202
00:11:08,145 --> 00:11:09,544
What's up, Ayumi?

203
00:11:09,545 --> 00:11:12,744
A skull?

204
00:11:12,745 --> 00:11:14,444
No joke?

205
00:11:14,445 --> 00:11:16,744
Why is a skull in a place like this?

206
00:11:16,745 --> 00:11:19,344
There are some more scattered here.

207
00:11:19,345 --> 00:11:20,544
What?

208
00:11:20,545 --> 00:11:24,844
The lower jaw, the upper forelimb, and the thighbone.

209
00:11:24,845 --> 00:11:26,544
Where's the body itself?

210
00:11:26,545 --> 00:11:27,545
Over there?

211
00:11:29,345 --> 00:11:31,345
What on earth?

212
00:11:33,045 --> 00:11:36,144
The person probably fell from that cliff!

213
00:11:36,145 --> 00:11:37,744
Yes, probably.

214
00:11:37,745 --> 00:11:40,044
These are most likely

215
00:11:40,045 --> 00:11:42,244
the bones of someone who fell quite some time ago.

216
00:11:42,245 --> 00:11:45,344
The bones may have scattered due to animals, rain and the wind.

217
00:11:45,345 --> 00:11:46,444
No.

218
00:11:46,445 --> 00:11:48,544
This is a homicide case,

219
00:11:48,545 --> 00:11:50,244
and an extremely heinous one too.

220
00:11:50,245 --> 00:11:51,544
-What? -What?

221
00:11:51,545 --> 00:11:53,644
Look, lime.

222
00:11:53,645 --> 00:11:57,644
Lime has the quality of giving off heat after sucking up liquid.

223
00:11:57,645 --> 00:12:00,144
When lime is scattered around the corpse and the nearby area,

224
00:12:00,145 --> 00:12:03,544
it has the quality of giving off heat after being wet by rain

225
00:12:03,545 --> 00:12:06,944
and as a result, the pace at which the body rots is quickened.

226
00:12:06,945 --> 00:12:10,444
Therefore, the body skeletonizes in a very short time.

227
00:12:10,445 --> 00:12:12,944
Maybe this skeleton is the Mr. Kono

228
00:12:12,945 --> 00:12:16,044
that everybody was talking about back at the inn?

229
00:12:16,045 --> 00:12:20,644
-No way. -But, he sent everybody the invitation card, didn't he?

230
00:12:20,645 --> 00:12:24,044
-It could be the man called Kono. -What?

231
00:12:24,045 --> 00:12:27,644
A ring and a cigarette case is under the rock.

232
00:12:27,645 --> 00:12:29,844
The letters carved on the ring are,

233
00:12:29,845 --> 00:12:32,644
ETSUKO to ASAO.

234
00:12:32,645 --> 00:12:35,344
It's most likely that Mr. Kono left these here,

235
00:12:35,345 --> 00:12:39,544
before the killer came back down here, after pushing him off the cliff.

236
00:12:39,545 --> 00:12:42,644
He left these here most probably as evidence that he was killed.

237
00:12:42,645 --> 00:12:45,844
But, maybe the killer left them here deliberately.

238
00:12:45,845 --> 00:12:47,244
If so, I think he'd leave it on Mr. Kono's finger

239
00:12:47,245 --> 00:12:48,544
after stripping him naked.

240
00:12:48,545 --> 00:12:52,144
Why would a killer who attempts to hide the identity of his victim

241
00:12:52,145 --> 00:12:55,144
deliberately hide something like that under a rock.

242
00:12:55,145 --> 00:12:56,744
Will somebody lend me a handkerchief?

243
00:12:56,745 --> 00:12:58,444
Okay.

244
00:12:58,445 --> 00:13:00,144
-Yes. -Thank you.

245
00:13:00,145 --> 00:13:03,244
Then, what's this cigarette box?

246
00:13:03,245 --> 00:13:05,444
If my deduction is correct,

247
00:13:05,445 --> 00:13:06,945
this is probably...

248
00:13:11,745 --> 00:13:14,344
All there is in here are cigarettes.

249
00:13:14,345 --> 00:13:16,744
Just as I thought.

250
00:13:16,745 --> 00:13:18,844
Don't tell me that...

251
00:13:18,845 --> 00:13:22,344
Yeah, this is what Mr. Kono left behind.

252
00:13:22,345 --> 00:13:23,944
It's a dying message.

253
00:13:23,945 --> 00:13:26,645
Dying message?

254
00:13:30,533 --> 00:13:32,233
What about this cigarette?

255
00:13:32,258 --> 00:13:35,757
Yeah, It's very likely that the man called Asao Kono left clues

256
00:13:35,758 --> 00:13:39,057
about who the killer before he was killed.

257
00:13:39,058 --> 00:13:44,357
But, isn't it just that two cigarettes out of six are torn?

258
00:13:44,358 --> 00:13:46,757
Watch closely.

259
00:13:46,758 --> 00:13:50,557
The two short cigarettes have filters on them, don't they?

260
00:13:50,558 --> 00:13:52,357
It goes to show that the cigarettes were deliberately torn short

